00:41:35.275 --> 00:41:40.516
your being and to have faith
that love affirms it,

00:41:40.516 --> 00:41:45.232
affirms that being.
Remember that self-admonition:

00:41:45.232 --> 00:41:49.090
not act like the
boyfriend but be.

00:41:49.090 --> 00:41:52.750
This is what Menelaus has to
ask forgiveness for.

00:41:52.750 --> 00:41:58.391
He didn't have enough faith in
love just to be and to accept

00:41:58.391 --> 00:42:03.362
the affirmation of his being
that Helen's reasonless,

00:42:03.362 --> 00:42:09.387
causeless love embodies.
Barth is asking a really

00:42:09.387 --> 00:42:16.083
serious question about the
compatibility between life and

00:42:16.083 --> 00:42:20.149
voice.
Remember that in "Ambrose His

00:42:20.149 --> 00:42:26.127
Mark" Ambrose is saved
from the bees lighting on his

00:42:26.127 --> 00:42:31.590
mouth because his mouth is on
his mother's breast.

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:37.987
He's asleep there having nursed.
It's as if the bees which

00:42:37.987 --> 00:42:42.487
signify eloquence if they land
on your mouth,

00:42:42.487 --> 00:42:47.500
they land on his eyes and on
his ears instead.

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:52.317
He can't have both that
connection with his mother and

00:42:52.317 --> 00:42:55.739
that kind of eloquence.
It's one or the other.

00:42:55.739 --> 00:42:58.517
You can't have love and
language somehow,

00:42:58.517 --> 00:43:02.405
and this is a very Freudian
understanding of how language

00:43:02.405 --> 00:43:05.278
works.
He tells a story about a child

00:43:05.278 --> 00:43:08.183
playing what's called the
"Fort-Da" game:

00:43:08.183 --> 00:43:10.710
here, away.
He has a little ball.

00:43:10.710 --> 00:43:14.059
A little two- or three-year-old
kid has a ball.

00:43:14.059 --> 00:43:16.920
He throws it away and then
retrieves it,

00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:21.468
he throws it away and retrieves
it, and Freud theorizes that he

00:43:21.468 --> 00:43:24.256
does that and he says,
"Fort, da, fort,

00:43:24.256 --> 00:43:26.569
da."
He does that because the

00:43:26.569 --> 00:43:30.518
language is a way of controlling
his mother's absence and the

00:43:30.518 --> 00:43:34.022
ball stands in for the mother.
It disappears and then it comes

00:43:34.022 --> 00:43:36.161
back.
It disappears and comes back,

00:43:36.161 --> 00:43:39.471
and at that time his mother,
who is actually Freud's

00:43:39.471 --> 00:43:42.976
daughter,
was going out to work for the

00:43:42.976 --> 00:43:48.147
first time on some days,
and the boy was getting used to

00:43:48.147 --> 00:43:52.008
letting her go.
So, language arises from

00:43:52.008 --> 00:43:55.333
that loss.
And Ambrose is only named once

00:43:55.333 --> 00:44:00.443
he's separated from his mother
and no longer nurses as a result

00:44:00.443 --> 00:44:05.457
of the bee incident,
and he also only gains a male

00:44:05.457 --> 00:44:09.725
name at that time.
And so, I think it's important

00:44:09.725 --> 00:44:14.473
that the masculinity of language
asserted with a talking sperm at

00:44:14.473 --> 00:44:18.553
the very beginning of this
collection is consistent with

00:44:18.553 --> 00:44:23.449
this sense that you become male
when you enter into language.

00:44:23.449 --> 00:44:27.329
Somehow when you're unnamed
you're not part of language;

00:44:27.329 --> 00:44:29.139
you're still connected to the
mother.

00:44:29.139 --> 00:44:30.420
And he actually had a female
name.

00:44:30.420 --> 00:44:33.730
Remember he's called Christine
for a while.

00:44:33.730 --> 00:44:40.719
So he becomes a boy after he's
separated from his mother.

00:44:40.719 --> 00:44:46.322
Menelaus's problem with Helen
suggests that incompatibility of

00:44:46.322 --> 00:44:51.246
being connected to the other,
and here across the line of

00:44:51.246 --> 00:44:55.860
gender, connected with the other
and somehow being able to be

00:44:55.860 --> 00:45:01.760
assimilated into language,
and the silence of the oracle

00:45:01.760 --> 00:45:05.429
on the question,
"Who am I?"

00:45:05.429 --> 00:45:08.133
This is on 158,
and you just get that blank,

00:45:08.133 --> 00:45:11.781
silence, and you can see it
enclosed in all those quotation

00:45:11.781 --> 00:45:14.830
marks.
This is Barth's effort to

00:45:14.830 --> 00:45:18.420
enclose the silence into
something readable,

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:23.679
to contain that impossibility
in the structure of the story.

00:45:23.679 --> 00:45:27.739
So all the quotation marks
suggest human voice.

00:45:27.739 --> 00:45:33.143
I want to suggest to you
finally that Barth is interested

00:45:33.143 --> 00:45:39.320
in the oral tradition above all
other traditions in this book.

00:45:39.320 --> 00:45:43.772
He's using Greek epic as the
source of his literary canon,

00:45:43.772 --> 00:45:47.674
here, and his canon of stories,
of narratives,

00:45:47.674 --> 00:45:53.162
because it's oral tradition
that brings the human voice and

00:45:53.162 --> 00:45:56.334
the human being,
the fact of a person,

00:45:56.334 --> 00:46:00.037
together most closely.
That's what fascinates him

00:46:00.037 --> 00:46:04.093
about the spoken word,
as opposed to the word you

00:46:04.093 --> 00:46:07.217
read.
And in other stories in this

00:46:07.217 --> 00:46:12.550
collection Barth experimented
with recording them with tape.

00:46:12.550 --> 00:46:15.168
So, these are stories,
some of them for voice and

00:46:15.168 --> 00:46:18.387
tape, and he'd do readings where
he'd go and he'd put a tape

00:46:18.387 --> 00:46:21.770
recorder on the podium and he'd
stand next to the tape recorder

00:46:21.770 --> 00:46:24.880
as his voice read the story from
the tape recorder.

00:46:24.880 --> 00:46:29.976
And it was all to dramatize the
problematic relationship between

00:46:29.976 --> 00:46:34.309
voice, story and person.
But I think the dream of

00:46:34.309 --> 00:46:38.371
Menelaus is that somehow that
voice can be residual,

00:46:38.371 --> 00:46:42.492
that somehow it can survive.
And, in that sense,

00:46:42.492 --> 00:46:47.626
I think it has something in
common with Nabokov's fantasy of

00:46:47.626 --> 00:46:52.855
the living artwork.
But, unlike Nabokov's fantasy,

00:46:52.855 --> 00:46:59.377
it requires this concept of
love, because love is what makes

00:46:59.377 --> 00:47:03.857
being into narrative.
It takes two,

00:47:03.857 --> 00:47:09.460
and it takes desire.
Desire moves narrative.

00:47:09.460 --> 00:47:13.009
And so at the end,
the comic ending of

00:47:13.009 --> 00:47:18.861
"Menelaiad," which echoes
the comic ending of Odysseus'

00:47:18.861 --> 00:47:22.027
trip back home,
of The Odyssey,

00:47:22.027 --> 00:47:25.660
he says:
Menelaus's story itself

00:47:25.660 --> 00:47:29.156
in ten or ten thousand years
expires, yet I'll survive it

00:47:29.156 --> 00:47:33.434
[Who is this "I"?],
I, in Proteus's terrifying last

00:47:33.434 --> 00:47:37.088
disguise, Beauty" spouse"s,
odd Elysium:

00:47:37.088 --> 00:47:42.375
the absurd,
unending possibility of

00:47:42.375 --> 00:47:47.759
love.
If you think that Barth in all

00:47:47.759 --> 00:47:52.943
his heady, intellectual,
canonical difficulty is

00:47:52.943 --> 00:47:58.679
uninterested in the world
outside of his fiction,

00:47:58.679 --> 00:48:03.993
I think you could argue that
it's on this notion of desire

00:48:03.993 --> 00:48:08.840
that he stakes his work's
connection to the world.

00:48:08.840 --> 00:48:12.104
And the echo of that desire is,
I would say,

00:48:12.104 --> 00:48:14.989
pleasure: something like,
in this case,

00:48:14.989 --> 00:48:19.164
Nabokov's aesthetic bliss,
but here it's more funny than

00:48:19.164 --> 00:48:20.000
that.

00:48:23.010 --> 00:48:27.376
It's not even so much the
transportation and the nostalgic

00:48:27.376 --> 00:48:30.900
quality of Nabokov's
description, sometimes.

00:48:30.900 --> 00:48:33.226
It's that wit,
that pleasurable wit,

00:48:33.226 --> 00:48:36.883
the pleasure we get reading,
being absorbed by something

00:48:36.883 --> 00:48:39.409
that we have to work hard to
read,

00:48:39.409 --> 00:48:42.560
and yet repays us with that
pleasure.

00:48:45.699 --> 00:48:49.884
When you read Crying of Lot
49 I'd like you to think

00:48:49.884 --> 00:48:54.501
about what that novel represents
in the relation between language

00:48:54.501 --> 00:48:56.960
and the world.
Is it similar?

00:48:56.960 --> 00:49:00.872
Barth and Pynchon are often
talked about as part of the same

00:49:00.872 --> 00:49:04.056
metafictional movement in this
couple of decades,

00:49:04.056 --> 00:49:06.790
'60s and '70s.
Are they assimilable to one

00:49:06.790 --> 00:49:10.000
another in these terms?
Think about that as you read.

